27/11/2005
ANKARA, Turkey -- An Ankara court on Thursday (24 November) issued life sentences for two members of the radical Islamic terror organisation Hizbullah. The two were convicted on charges of attempting to overthrow the Turkish constitutional order. The court also jailed three other Hizbullah members -- one for nine years, and two for seven years -- for involvement in an illegal enterprise. Six other people were acquitted. 
In other news, top Turkish government and military officials met on Friday to discuss the security situation in the country. According to a brief statement after the talks, the participants agreed on a set of measures to be undertaken against crime and terrorism. (NTV, TurkishPress.com, Turks.US - 25/11/05)
